# Claude Code Rules for akkai-3d

## Architecture & Structure

### Module Structure
- Each domain module MUST have: `controllers/`, `services/`, `use-cases/`, `entities/`, `dto/`, `docs/`
- Services contain business logic; use-cases orchestrate complex flows
- Never mix presentation logic with business logic
- Modules should be independent; use imports to manage dependencies

### Path Aliases (Required)
- ALWAYS use path aliases (@auth/*, @venda/*, @produto/*, etc) instead of ../../../
- Import order: external libraries → path aliases → local files
- Update tsconfig.json paths when adding new modules
- Jest moduleNameMapper in package.json mirrors tsconfig paths

## Design Principles: OOP, SOLID & DRY

### Single Responsibility Principle (SRP)
- **One class, one reason to change**
- Services handle business logic
- Controllers handle HTTP only
- Use-cases orchestrate complex workflows
- Repositories handle data access
- Guards/filters handle cross-cutting concerns (auth, validation, error handling)
- Example: Don't put database logic in a service that should only handle calculations

### Open/Closed Principle (OCP)
- **Open for extension, closed for modification**
- Use inheritance and interfaces for extensibility
- Create new classes instead of modifying existing ones
- Use NestJS dependency injection (Providers) for flexibility
- Example: Create `BaseService` for common logic instead of copy-pasting

### Liskov Substitution Principle (LSP)
- Subtypes must be substitutable for parent types
- Interfaces must be properly implemented
- Don't break contracts in subclasses
- Example: All repositories should follow the same interface pattern

### Interface Segregation Principle (ISP)
- Create specific, small interfaces instead of fat general ones
- Clients shouldn't depend on interfaces they don't use
- Example: `IVendaRepository` with vendas-specific methods, not a generic `IRepository`

### Dependency Inversion Principle (DIP)
- Depend on abstractions (interfaces), not concrete implementations
- Use NestJS constructor injection for dependencies
- Use providers for testability and flexibility
- Example: Inject `IVendaRepository` interface, not `VendaRepository` class directly

### DRY (Don't Repeat Yourself)
- **No copy-pasted code**
- Extract common logic to helper methods/services
- Use inheritance for shared behavior
- Common validation/transformation → common modules
- Repeated patterns → reusable decorators or utilities
- Example: Don't duplicate date formatting in multiple services; create a utility function

## Code Quality Standards

### DTOs & Validation
- MANDATORY: use `class-validator` decorators in all DTOs
- Use: @IsString(), @IsNumber(), @IsEmail(), @IsOptional(), @IsUUID(), @IsArray(), etc
- DTOs never contain business logic
- Add @ApiProperty() decorators for Swagger documentation
- Validation error messages should be user-friendly

### TypeORM & Database
- ALWAYS use TypeORM entities + repositories (never raw queries)
- Use lazy loading (lazy: true) for heavy relationships
- Create migrations for EVERY schema change (no synchronize: true in production)
- Foreign keys must have explicit onDelete: 'CASCADE' or 'SET NULL'
- Paginate list endpoints (never SELECT * without LIMIT)
- Use TypeORM query builder for complex queries over raw SQL
- Entities must have proper indexes for frequently queried fields
- **NEW ENTITIES MUST BE ADDED to the entities array in `src/config/database.config.ts`** (critical - easy to forget!)
- Export all entities from module's `index.ts` file for clean imports

### Exceptions & Error Handling
- Throw NestJS exceptions (NotFoundException, BadRequestException, ConflictException, etc)
- ProblemDetailsExceptionFilter automatically formats responses
- Never silently catch errors with empty .catch()
- Log errors with context for debugging
- Don't throw generic Error; use typed NestJS exceptions

### Testing
- **MANDATORY: .spec.ts file for EVERY service and controller**
- **MANDATORY: All public methods must be covered by tests**
- Target minimum 80% overall code coverage (npm run test:cov)
- Critical modules require 90%+ coverage: auth, venda, financeiro, produto
- Use @nestjs/testing with Test.createTestingModule()
- Don't mock database in repository unit tests (test with real entities)
- Test both happy path and error cases
- **maxWorkers=1 is ENFORCED in jest.config.js** — prevents concurrency issues (shared resources, database access)
  - All tests automatically use maxWorkers=1, no need to add the flag
  - Jest will fail if someone tries to change this setting
- Run tests with: npm run test
- Run single test: npm run test -- filename.spec.ts
- Check coverage: npm run test:cov
- If coverage drops below target, code review should reject the PR

## Naming Conventions

**ALL classes, methods, properties, and variables MUST be in Portuguese.**

- **Entities**: PascalCase singular in Portuguese (Venda, Produto, Assinante, Carteira, not vendas or sales)
- **Controllers**: *Controller (VendaController, ProdutoController)
- **Services**: *Service (VendaService, FeiraService)
- **Use-cases**: VerbNounUseCase (InserirVendaUseCase, AlterarFeiraUseCase, ExcluirVendaUseCase)
- **DTOs**: *Dto suffix (CriarVendaDto, AtualizarProdutoDto, FiltrarVendaDto)
- **Variables/properties**: camelCase Portuguese (nomeVenda, preçoProduto, dataInicio, statusAtivo)
- **Methods**: camelCase Portuguese, start with verb (criarVenda, obterPorId, alterarCarteira, listarPorFeira, validarEstoque)
- **Boolean methods/properties**: start with é/tem/pode (éAtivo, temPermissão, podeExcluir)
- **Comments & strings**: Portuguese (comments should explain the WHY, not the WHAT)
- **Do NOT mix English and Portuguese** in the same file/class
- **Database column names**: snake_case Portuguese (nome_venda, preco_produto, data_inicio)

## Configuration & Environment

- NEVER hardcode values (URLs, keys, timeouts, ports, paths)
- All config via ConfigService from @nestjs/config
- Validate env variables in src/config/env.validation.ts at startup
- Environment variables checked on bootstrap - fail fast
- Sensitive data (passwords, keys) never committed to git

## Best Practices

### Async Code
- MANDATORY: use async/await (not .then() chains)
- Add `void` prefix to unawaited Promises (void this.sendEmail())
- Never forget await on async operations

### Swagger Documentation
- Add @ApiOperation() to all endpoint methods
- Add @ApiResponse() for success and error cases
- Document DTOs with @ApiProperty()
- Keep Swagger synchronized with code
- Swagger available at /api/docs

### Code Style & Formatting
- Run `npm run format` (Prettier auto-format before committing)
- Run `npm run lint` (ESLint with auto-fix before committing)
- Always commit formatted code
- TypeScript strict mode enabled - no any types without // @ts-ignore comment

### Git Commits (Portuguese)
- Pattern: `type: description`
- Types: feat (feature), fix (bugfix), refactor (code restructure), test (tests), docs (documentation), chore (maintenance)
- Examples: `feat: adiciona filtro por carteira`, `fix: corrige erro de validação`, `refactor: simplifica lógica de venda`
- Commit messages are the primary communication to teammates

## Claude Never Commits Code

**CRITICAL RULE: Claude should NEVER create commits. Always let the user commit.**

- Never use `git commit` or `git add`
- Claude prepares changes but user must stage and commit
- User retains full control of what gets committed
- This prevents accidentally committing incomplete work or wrong changes

---

## Before Every Commit (User Checklist)

- [ ] **Tests written for ALL new/modified public methods** (services, controllers)
- [ ] `npm run test` all passing (no skipped/pending tests)
- [ ] `npm run test:cov` coverage >= 80% overall (90%+ for auth, venda, financeiro, produto)
- [ ] **ALL classes, methods, and properties are in Portuguese** (no English names)
- [ ] **Code follows OOP, SOLID, and DRY principles** (no code duplication)
- [ ] Each class has single responsibility (SRP)
- [ ] Use interfaces for dependencies (DIP)
- [ ] Use path aliases for all imports (@venda/*, @auth/*, etc)
- [ ] All DTOs have class-validator decorators
- [ ] **NEW ENTITIES added to entities array in `src/config/database.config.ts`** (if created new entity)
- [ ] `npm run lint` passed (with auto-fix applied)
- [ ] `npm run format` applied (code is formatted)
- [ ] Migrations created (if database schema changed)
- [ ] Swagger decorators added to new/modified endpoints
- [ ] No hardcoded config values (use ConfigService)
- [ ] No console.log() in production code (use logger)
- [ ] Commit message in Portuguese with type prefix

## Module-Specific Guidelines

### Auth Module
- JWT secrets never logged or exposed
- Password hashing uses bcrypt
- Roles and permissions checked via decorators
- Refresh tokens managed separately from access tokens

### Venda (Sales) Module
- Use-cases for complex sales workflows (inserir, alterar, excluir)
- PrecoProdutoFeira sync logic in services
- Feira (market) filtering critical for venda listings

### Produto (Product) Module
- MovimentacaoEstoque (stock movement) must be transactional
- CategoriaProduto hierarchy validation
- Stock levels validated before sales

### Assinatura (Subscription) Module
- CicloAssinatura (cycle) lifecycle management
- KitMensal (monthly kit) item relationships
- Plan changes handled with use-cases

### Financeiro (Financial) Module
- Carteira (wallet) transactions logged
- TaxaMeioPagamentoCarteira (payment method tax) applied correctly
- Despesa (expense) categorization mandatory
